\n\n<u>Arles</u>\nArles is a city and commune in the south of France, in the Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne department, of which it is a subprefecture, in the former province of Provence.\nA large part of the Camargue is located on the territory of the commune, making it the largest commune in Metropolitan France in terms of territory. \nThe city has a long history, and was of considerable importance in the Roman province of Gallia Narbonensis. The Roman and Romanesque Monuments of Arles were listed as UNESCO World Heritage Sites in 1981. The Dutch post-Impressionist painter Vincent van Gogh lived in Arles from 1888 to 1889 and produced over 300 paintings and drawings during his time there. An international photography festival has been held in the city since 1970.\nThe river Rh\u00f4ne forks into two branches just upstream of Arles, forming the Camargue delta.\n\nPopulation: 52,500 (approx)\nElevation: 0 - 57m\nArea: 758.93 km2\nDensity: 69/km2\nCoordinates: 43\u00b040\u203236\u2033N 4\u00b037\u203240\u2033E\n\n[ Source + more: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arles\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia - Arles</a> ]\n", "Format": "image/jpeg", "Legacy IPTCDigest": "9F574B51CB2A7E886735D99610A65499", "Sub Sec Time Digitized": "47", "History When": "2015:10:13 10:41:49+02:00", "Photoshop Thumbnail": "(Binary data 6854 bytes, use -b option to extract)", "History Software Agent": "Adobe Photoshop Lightroom 5.3 (Windows)", "Color Transform": "YCbCr", "Artist": "Perry Tak", "Country": "France", "Focal Plane Resolution Unit": "inches", "History Changed": "/", "Measurement Observer": "CIE 1931", "Image Description": "<b>Place du Forum</b> 19/06/2015 19h05\n<i>Ap\u00e9ro</i> or <i>une tasse de caf\u00e9</i>, life in the Arles has also too many choices. \n\nThis candid is taken on the of <i>Mon Bar Tabac Brasserie</i>, Place du Forum. \n\n<u>Arles</u>\nArles is a city and commune in the south of France, in the Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne department, of which it is a subprefecture, in the former province of Provence.\nA large part of the Camargue is located on the territory of the commune, making it the largest commune in Metropolitan France in terms of territory. \nThe city has a long history, and was of considerable importance in the Roman province of Gallia Narbonensis. Park</u>\nBattery Park is a 10 ha public park located at the Battery, the southern tip of Manhattan Island in New York City, facing New York Harbor. The Battery is named for the artillery batteries that were positioned there in the city's early years to protect the settlement behind them.\nThe southern shoreline of Manhattan Island had long been known as the Battery, and was a popular promenade since the 17th century. At the time, an artillery battery there served as protection to the town. The Battery was the center of Evacuation Day celebrations commemorating the departure of the last British troops in the United States after the American Revolutionary War. Just prior to the War of 1812, the West Battery, later renamed Castle Clinton, was erected on a small artificial offshore island nearby, to replace the earlier batteries in the area; later, when the land of Battery Park was created, it encircled and incorporated the island.\nThe relatively modern park was mostly created by landfill starting from 1855, resulting in a landscaped open space at the foot of the heavily developed mainland of downtown. Skyscrapers now occupy most of the original land, stopping abruptly where the park begins. On State Street, the former harbor front and the northern boundary of the park, a single Federal mansion, the James Watson House, survives as part of the Shrine of Saint Elizabeth Ann Seton; until the 1820s, the city's stylish residential district was north of this house, between Broadway and the Hudson River.\n[ Source: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battery_Park\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia - Battery Park</a> ]\n", "Format": "image/jpeg", "Legacy IPTCDigest": "700EA48666D6324367EDB629D23F8FF2", "Sub Sec Time Digitized": "88", "History When": "2015:05:08 13:55:59+02:00", "Photoshop Thumbnail": "(Binary data 6476 bytes, use -b option to extract)", "History Software Agent": "Adobe Photoshop Lightroom 5.3 (Windows)", "Color Transform": "YCbCr", "Artist": "Perry Tak", "Country": "United States", "Focal Plane Resolution Unit": "inches", "History Changed": "/", "Measurement Observer": "CIE 1931", "Image Description": "<b>Battery Park</b> 27/04/2015 10h07\nBut first of all a cup of hot coffee at <i>Table Green</i> in Battery Park to celebrate the sunshine and the fact that we made it all the way to New York! \n\n<u>Battery Park</u>\nBattery Park is a 10 ha public park located at the Battery, the southern tip of Manhattan Island in New York City, facing New York Harbor.
